  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 25-41.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - We reach here the second interruption in the account of Caleb's posterity. (A) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Jerahmeel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", though the eldest Hezronite son, has as yet been passed by in favour of Ram and in favour of Caleb, so far as regards part of his descendants. Jerahmeel himself is mentioned nowhere else, but his people collectively are (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 27:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 30:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). On the other hand, this place ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "alone",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " supplies the lists of names, and we have not the aid of any collation. Ver. 25 purports in the Authorized Version to give five sons of Jerahmeel by his first wife, of name not given. The absence of the conjunction \"and,\" however, in the Hebrew text before the last name, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Ahijah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", suggests that this may be the name of the first wife the presence of which seems greatly required by the contents of the next verse. Some particle being required, Le Clerc, accepting the suggestion of Junins and Tremellius, proposes to supply ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "מֵאֵת",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Bertheau the same preposition, but in a simpler form, prefixed to the name Ahijah (see Barrington's 'Genealogies,' 1:180). 1 Chronicles 2:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The family of Jerahmeel, the first-born of Hezron, which inhabited a part of the Negeb of Judah called after him the south of the Jerahmeelites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 27:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 30:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:25",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Chronicles 2:25",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Four sons were born to Jerahmeel by his first wife. Five names indeed follow; but as the last, אחיּה, although met with elsewhere as a man's name, is not ranged with the others by ו copul., as those that precede are with each other, it appears to be the name of a woman, and probably a מ has fallen out after the immediately preceding ם. So Cler., J. H. Mich., Berth. This conjecture gains in probability from the mention in 1 Chronicles 2:26 of another wife, whence we might expect that in 1 Chronicles 2:25 the first wife would be named.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Four sons were born to Jerahmeel by his first wife. Five names indeed follow; but as the last, אחיּה, although met with elsewhere as a man's name, is not ranged with the others by ו copul., as those that precede are with each other, it appears to be the name of a woman, and probably a מ has fallen out after the immediately preceding ם. So Cler., J. H. Mich., Berth. This conjecture gains in probability from the mention in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Chronicles 2:26",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " of another wife, whence we might expect that in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Chronicles 2:25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " the first wife would be named.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
